# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alibaba-cloud
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] Alibaba Cloud offers cloud services that are available on a pay-as-you-go basis, and include elastic compute, data storage, relational databases, big-data processing, DDoS protection and content delivery networks (CDN).
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] It is the largest cloud computing company in China, and in Asia Pacific according to Gartner.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] Alibaba Cloud operates data centers in 29 regions and 87 availability zones around the globe.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] As of June 2017, Alibaba Cloud is placed in the Visionaries' quadrant of Gartner's Magic Quadrant for cloud infrastructure as a service, worldwide.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] Alibaba Cloud was founded in September 2009, and R&D centers and operation centers were opened in Hangzhou, Beijing, and Silicon Valley.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] In November 2010, the company supported the first Single's Day (11.11) Taobao shopping festival, with 2.4 billion PageViews (PV) in 24 hours.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] Two years later, in November 2012, it became the first Chinese cloud service provider to pass ISO27001:2005 (Information Security Management System).
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] In January 2013, Alibaba Cloud merged with HiChina (founded by Xiangning Zhang) for the www.net.cn business as one of the largest acquisitions in the company's history at the time.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] In August of that year, ApsaraDB architecture supported 5000 physical machines in a single cluster.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] The company's Hong Kong data center went online in May 2014, and in December of that year, Alibaba Cloud defended a 14-hour-long DDoS attack, peaking at 453.8 Gbit/s.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] In July 2015, the Alibaba Group invested US$1 billion in Alibaba Cloud.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] A month later, Alibaba Cloud's first Singapore data center opened, and Singapore was announced as Alibaba Cloud's overseas headquarters.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] Two US data centers went online in October 2015, and that same month MaxCompute took the lead in the Sort Benchmark, sorting 100 TB data in 377s compared with Apache Spark's previous record of 1406s.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] The Alibaba Cloud Computing Conference was also held in October 2015 in Hangzhou and attracted over 20,000 developers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] A month later, in November, the company supported the 11.11 shopping festival with a record of $14.2 billion transactions in 24 hours.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] Alibaba Cloud partnered with SK Holdings C&C in April 2016 to provide cloud services to Korean and Chinese companies.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] A month later, the company formalized a joint venture with SoftBank to launch cloud services in Japan that utilize technologies and solutions from Alibaba Cloud.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] In June 2016, Alibaba Cloud expanded its data center operations in Singapore with the establishment of a second availability zone.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] Alibaba Cloud also achieved two new certifications overseas: Singapore Multi-Tier Cloud Security (MTCS) standard Level 3, and the Payment Card Industry Three-Domain Secure (PCI 3DS).
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] The company partnered with Vodafone Germany in November 2016 for Data Center operations and to provide cloud services to German and European companies.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] Alibaba became the official cloud services provider of the Olympics in January 2017.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] A month later, in February, the company became a founding Member of the EU Cloud Code of Conduct.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] In June 2017, Alibaba Cloud was placed in the Visionaries quadrant of Gartner's Magic Quadrant for Cloud Infrastructure as a Service, Worldwide.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] Alibaba Cloud partnered with Malaysia's Fusionex in September 2017 to provide cloud solutions in Southeast Asia, and the Malaysia data center commenced operations in October.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] That same month, the company partnered with Elastic and launched a new service called Alibaba Cloud Elasticsearch.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] Alibaba Cloud India data center commenced operations in December 2017.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] In addition, Alibaba Cloud received the C5 standard certification from the German Federal Office for Information Security (BSI) for its data centers in Germany and Singapore.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] In February 2018, Alibaba Cloud's Indonesia data center commenced operations.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] The company's first data center opening in the Philippines in June 2021.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] Alibaba Cloud unveiled the ARM-based Yitian 710 chip, designed in-house, for use in its data centers in October 2021.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] On November 24, 2021, the bug Log4Shell was disclosed to Apache by Chen Zhaojun of Alibaba Cloud's Security Team.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] On December 22, 2021, the Chinese Ministry of Industry and Information Technology suspended a partnership with Alibaba Cloud for "failure in reporting cybersecurity vulnerabilities" related to the Log4Shell bug.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] In September 2022, Alibaba Cloud announced a $1 billion pledge to upgrade its global partner ecosystem.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] Alibaba Cloud has 25 regional data centres globally.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] The Data Center in Germany is operated by Vodafone Germany (Frankfurt) and certified with C5.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] Alibaba Cloud provides cloud computing IaaS, PaaS, DBaaS and SaaS, including services such as e-commerce, big data, Database, IoT, Object storage (OSS), Kubernetes and data customization which can be managed from Alibaba web page or using `aliyun` command line tool.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] AnalyticDB was first released in May 2018, and the latest version 3.0 was released in 2019.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] On April 26, 2019, TPC published TPC-DS benchmark result of AnalyticDB.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] In 2019, a paper about the system design of AnalyticDB was published in VLDB conference 2019.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] On October 26, 2016, Zhang Kai, CEO of ITHome issued an announcement stating he could no longer tolerate Alibaba Cloud's overselling and service interruption issues, and had migrated the hosting entirely to Baidu Cloud.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-cloud] Alibaba Cloud subsequently issued an apology letter, but indirectly mentioned that website performance should consider system architecture and avoid single-point design.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] On 19 September 2014, Alibaba's American initial public offering (IPO) on the New York Stock Exchange raised US$25 billion, giving the company a market value of US$231 billion and, by far, then the largest IPO in world history.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It is one of the top 10 most valuable corporations, and is named the 31st-largest public company in the world on the *Forbes* Global 2000 2020 list.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In January 2018, Alibaba became the second Asian company to break the US$500 billion valuation mark, after its competitor Tencent.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba is one of the world's largest retailers and e-commerce companies.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2020, it was also rated as the fifth-largest artificial intelligence company.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The company hosts the largest B2B (Alibaba.com), C2C (Taobao), and B2C (Tmall) marketplaces in the world.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It has been expanding into the media industry, with revenues rising by triple percentage points year after year.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It also set the record on the 2018 edition of China's Singles' Day, the world's biggest online and offline shopping day.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The company's name came from the character Ali Baba from the Middle Eastern folk-tale collection *One Thousand and One Nights* because of its universal appeal.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] On 28 June 1999, Jack Ma, with 17 friends and students founded Alibaba.com, a China-based B2B marketplace site, in his Hangzhou apartment.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In October 1999, Alibaba received a US$25 million investment from Investor AB, Goldman Sachs and SoftBank.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 1999, Investor AB owned 6% of the shares.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] When eBay announced its expansion into China in 2003, Ma viewed the American company as a foreign competitor and created Taobao as a subsidiary to try and win the domestic market.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Taobao gained consumer trust in the Chinese e-commerce market with features like third party verification and offering most services for free before making a return on additional services.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Taobao surpassed eBay in 2007, and eBay later closed its unprofitable China Web unit.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2005, Yahoo! invested in Alibaba through a variable interest entity (VIE) structure, buying a 40% stake in the company for US$1 billion.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2012, China Investment Corporation led a group of Chinese investors in buying out Yahoo!'s 40% stake and in buying the Alibaba shares that had traded on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] According to Li Chuan, a senior executive at Alibaba, the company was planning in 2013 to open traditional brick and mortar retail outlets in partnership with Wanda Group, a Chinese real estate company.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Additionally, Alibaba purchased a 25% stake in Hong Kong-listed Chinese department store chain Intime Retail in early 2014.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In early 2017, Alibaba and Intime's founder Shen Guojun agreed to pay HK$19.8 billion (US$2.6 billion) to take the store chain private.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba's stake—28% from 2014's US$692 million investment—rose about 74% after the deal.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In April 2014, Alibaba invested in Lyft, along with Coatue Management, and Andreessen Horowitz; they led a US$250 million Series D financing round.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] On 5 June 2014, Alibaba bought a 50% stake of Guangzhou Evergrande F.C. from Evergrande Real Estate Group Ltd. in a deal that was worth 1.2 billion yuan (US$192 million).
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] On 5 September 2014, Alibaba set a US$60- to $66- per-share price range for its scheduled initial public offering (IPO).
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] On 18 September 2014, Alibaba's IPO priced at US$68, raising US$25 billion for the company and investors.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba was the biggest IPO in history, bigger than Google, Facebook, and Twitter combined.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] On 22 September 2014, Alibaba's underwriters announced their confirmation that they had exercised a greenshoe option to sell 15% more shares than originally planned.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba and the underwriters of its IPO were sued in a California superior court in a consolidated class action lawsuit.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The lawsuit was filed in October 2015 on behalf of investors who purchased Alibaba's American depositary shares alleging violations of the Securities Act.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba reached a settlement agreement in December 2018, subject to court approval, in which it agreed to pay $75 million to settle the lawsuit.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2015, Alibaba's Mobile Business Group formed Ali Literature to enter the internet literature sector.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Beginning in mid-2015, Alibaba invested in Paytm, an India-based mobile payment platform.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba is among the most prominent investors in Thailand's Eastern Economic Corridor, which was opened in 2018.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba committed approximately US$320 million for the development of an e-commerce digital hub in the EEC.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In January 2017, Alibaba and the International Olympic Committee jointly announced an $800 million deal that would last until 2028 where the company would sponsor the Olympic Games.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In September 2018, Jack Ma, the main founder of Alibaba, announced that he would step down as chairman in a year's time so he could focus on philanthropy.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In response to the announcement, *The Economist* stated that Ma had a significant impact in China and worldwide.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] On Tuesday, 10 September 2019, Jack Ma officially stepped down as the chairman of Alibaba, and Daniel Zhang succeeded him at the head of the company.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In November 2019, Alibaba raised 12.9 billion in its secondary listing in Hong Kong, which became the world's largest offering that year.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In November 2020, Chinese leader Xi Jinping blocked the Ant Group IPO.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Economist Bo Zhuang stated the block was part of the CCP's increased scrutiny of finance and technology companies.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In December 2020, the shares of Alibaba Group suffered a stock price crash to the lowest close in around 6 months, following the antitrust investigation into the company by Chinese regulators.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In December 2020, China's State Administration for Market Regulation (SAMR) stated that it opened an investigation into Alibaba over monopolistic practices.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The country's central bank, as well as three other regulators, confirmed in a separate statement that the affiliated Ant Group would also be summoned for discussions over "competition and consumer rights", where regulators instructed the company to return its focus to digital-payments.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] *People's Daily*, the official newspaper of the Central Committee of the Chinese Communist Party, endorsed the investigation shortly after the announcement, claiming the investigation to be "an important step in strengthening antimonopoly oversight in the internet sphere".
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] As a result, from the antitrust probe, Alibaba lost nearly all of its stock-market gains in 2020, from $859 billion to $586 billion, by the end of December.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Jack Ma, co-founder of both Alibaba and Ant Group, vanished from public view when Ant's IPO was suspended in early November, but resurfaced in January 2021 in a 50-second video, appearing briefly via video link at the digitally facilitated Rural Teacher Initiative.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] As of February 2021, he has yet to be seen in public.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The video appearance caused Alibaba stock to increase 7%.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Jack Ma made a public appearance in Hangzhou, China in March 2023 where he met with students and teachers at the Alibaba partners-funded Yungu School.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In February 2021, Alibaba sold $5 billion in bonds, the company's third large sale of dollar bonds, issuing four sets priced to yield between 2.143% and 3.251%.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The four sets of bonds were $1.5 billion of both 10-year and 30-year debt along with $1 billion of bonds due in 20 and 40 years.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The 20-year bonds were designated as sustainability notes.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] On 9 April 2021, as part of a Chinese crackdown on big tech, SAMR issued a $2.8 billion fine against Alibaba for anti-competitive practices and ordered Alibaba to file self-examination and compliance reports to the SAMR for three years.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] This amounted to 12% Archived 3 June 2021 at the Wayback Machine of its 2020 net profit.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Critics say the move tightens the Chinese's governments control of tech companies.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba stated that it would dedicate itself to correct its errors and accepted the fine without making any appeal.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] On 11 November 2021, it was reported that over the course of its 11-day Singles' Day sales extravaganza, Chinese e-commerce giant Alibaba Group Holding received 540.3 billion yuan (S$114.4 billion) in orders, a 14 percent increase over the previous year.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In July 2022, the SEC added Alibaba to a list of companies facing delisting from U.S. stock exchanges if its auditors remain unable to examine Alibaba's books before 2024.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In December 2022, a state-owned enterprise of the China Internet Investment Fund, established by the Cyberspace Administration of China, took a 1 percent golden share investment in two Alibaba subsidiaries that control Youku and UCWeb.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Each business unit would have their own CEO and board of directors and be able to seek their own fundraising and market listings.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Under the new "1+6+N" structure, Alibaba also established a Capital Management Committee and a Compliance and Risk Committee.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] *The Wall Street Journal* reported on 30 March that Jack Ma engineered this in talks with company CEO Daniel Zhang while he was overseas.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In September 2023, Cainiao Smart Logistics Network Ltd., the logistics arm of Alibaba Group, has filed for its Hong Kong initial public offering, potentially making it among the first of the Chinese e-commerce leader's units to go public.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In December 2024, Alibaba announced it would sell Intime Department Store to Youngor Group.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In November 2025, the *Financial Times* published a report stating that a U.S. national security memo accused Alibaba of providing capabilities to the People's Liberation Army used to target the U.S.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In January 2026, Texas governor Greg Abbott prohibited Alibaba products and services on all government devices and networks.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In June 2026 the U.S. added the company to its list of "Chinese military companies." Alibaba subsequently filed a lawsuit against the U.S. government in an attempt to be removed from the list.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba is viewed by the Chinese government as one of its national champion corporations.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba supplies a significant amount of technology for the Digital Silk Road.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Buyers who visit Alibaba.com are looking to purchase wholesale from thousands of product categories.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba.com later became the world's largest online B2B trading platform for small businesses as of 2014.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] According to Alibaba.com's own website, there are 150,000 verified sellers located in more than 200 countries around the world.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It also indicates that there are more than 10 million buyers around the world.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2019, Alibaba.com allowed small and medium-sized U.S. businesses to sell on the site, and the company was actively looking to tap into the B2B e-commerce market in the US.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The opportunity provided US business-to-business companies with the ability to also sell to other US retailers and smaller commercial outfits.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2019, one-third of buyers on the site were US-based, while more than 95% of sellers were from China.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba.com has three main services: the English language portal Alibaba.com, which handles sales between importers and exporters from nearly all countries, the Chinese portal 1688.com, which manages domestic B2B trade in China, and AliExpress.com, a global consumer marketplace.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba.com went public at the Hong Kong Stock Exchange in 2007, and was delisted again in 2012.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Two years later in 2014, Alibaba.com was privately held again following a $2.5 billion buyback.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2013, 1688.com launched a direct channel that was responsible for $30 million in daily transaction value.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2003, Alibaba launched Taobao Marketplace (淘宝网), offering a variety of products for retail sales.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Taobao grew to become China's largest C2C online shopping platform and later became the second most visited website in China, according to Alexa Internet.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Taobao's growth was attributed to offering free registration and commission-free transactions using a free third-party payment platform.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Advertising made up 75 percent of the company's total revenue, allowing it to break even in 2009.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2010, Taobao's profit was estimated to be ¥1.5 billion (US$235.7 million), which was only about 0.4 percent of their total sales figure of ¥400 billion (US$62.9 billion) that year, way below the industry average of 2 percent, according to iResearch estimates.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In April 2008, Taobao introduced a spin-off, Taobao Mall (淘宝商城, later Tmall.com), an online retail platform to complement the Taobao C2C portal, offering global brands to an increasingly affluent Chinese consumer base.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It became the eighth most visited web site in China as of 2013.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2012, Tmall.com later changed its Chinese name to Tianmao (天猫, "sky cat"), reflecting Tmall's Chinese pronunciation.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In March 2010, Taobao launched the group shopping website Juhuasuan (聚划算), offering "flash sales", which are products that are available at a discount for only a fixed time period.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In October 2010, Taobao beta-launched eTao, a comparison shopping website that offers search results from mostly Chinese online shopping platforms, including product searches, sales and coupon searches.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] According to the Alibaba Group web site, eTao offers products from Amazon China, Dangdang, Gome, Yihaodian, Nike China, and Vancl, as well as Taobao and Tmall.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] As part of a restructuring of Taobao by Alibaba, these spin-offs became separate companies in 2011, with Tmall and eTao becoming separate businesses in June and Juhuasuan becoming a separate business later in October.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2010, Alibaba launched AliExpress.com, an online retail service made up of mostly small Chinese businesses offering products to international online buyers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It is the most visited e-commerce platform in Russia.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It allows small businesses in China to sell to customers all over the world, resulting in a wide variety of products.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It might be more accurate to compare AliExpress to eBay, though, as sellers are independent; it simply serves as a host for other businesses to sell to consumers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Similar to eBay, sellers on Aliexpress can be either companies or individuals.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It connects Chinese businesses directly with buyers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The main difference from Taobao is that it's aimed primarily at international buyers, mainly the US, Russia, Brazil and Spain.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2012, Alibaba instituted its Public Dispute Resolution Center, which crowdsources buyers and sellers to vote on transactional rules and decide the outcome of disputes on the platform.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] This decentralized approach was popular and similar mechanisms were adopted or experimented with by other e-commerce platforms in China.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] On 11 June 2014, Alibaba launched US shopping site 11 Main.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The 11 Main marketplace hosts merchants in categories such as clothing, fashion accessories and jewelry as well as interior goods and arts and crafts and it plans to keep adding more, said the company.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] On 23 June 2015, Alibaba announced that it is selling 11 Main to OpenSky, an online-marketplace operator based in New York.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In February 2015, Alibaba invests US$590 million in Meizu, acquiring an undisclosed minority stake.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2016, Alibaba acquired control of Singapore-based e-commerce platform Lazada.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Lazada is the largest e-commerce platform in southeast Asia, with a major presence in Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand, and Vietnam.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] This acquisition increased integration on Alibaba between Chinese merchants and their customers in southeast Asia.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In October 2016, Alibaba launched Alitrip, later named Fliggy, an online travel platform that is designed as an online mall for brands such as airline companies and agencies.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Fliggy set the target audience as the younger generation and it strives to become a one-stop service when they plan their trips, particularly in overseas travel.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] On 7 August 2017, Alibaba Group and Marriott International hotel group announced a comprehensive strategic co-operation.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Two companies will set up a joint venture company.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Through the docking technology system and the superiority resources, Fliggy has Marriott hotel flagship store.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It has the same function with Marriott Chinese website and Marriott mobile app to create the best global travel experience for consumers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2016, the Office of the United States Trade Representative added Taobao back onto a list of notorious counterfeit platforms that includes the likes of torrent site The Pirate Bay.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba denied wrongdoing and filed two lawsuits against the counterfeiters as of 4 January 2017, but brands whose sales have been affected by the counterfeit products accused Alibaba of not doing enough.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2017, Alibaba started opening a chain of supermarkets, named Freshippo (or Hema; 盒马), as part of the company's "new retail strategy," where customers can either order in the store or online for delivery in under 30 minutes.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It offers a mobile app that recommends customers products based on data analytics.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In addition, customers can have their groceries cooked to eat in the food court of the supermarket.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In October 2018, it was reported that Alibaba's Koubei have merged with online food delivery service platform Ele.me into a new local life service subsidiary.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] However, the newly formed Alibaba Local Life Service entity experienced major competition from local service giant Meituan, which is backed by Tencent, leading to rumours of planned layoffs in 2022.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In September 2019, Alibaba announced it would acquire Chinese e-commerce platform Kaola from NetEase for around US$2 billion.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In October 2020, Alibaba agreed to pay US$3.6 billion to take control of China's biggest hypermarket operator Sun Art (SEHK: 6808) from French billionaire Mulliez family.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The deal doubled the group's stake in the hypermarket chain with a total ownership of 72%.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba.com offers a paid Gold Supplier membership to try to ensure that each seller is genuine; sellers' Gold Supplier status and the number of years it has been held are displayed.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The supplier verification types and checks are listed on Alibaba.com's website, with more stringent checks for sellers outside China.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] While the majority of suppliers are reported to be genuine, there have been many cases of sellers, some with Gold Supplier status, seeking to defraud unsuspecting buyers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In February 2011, controversy ensued when Alibaba's corporate office admitted that it had granted the mark of integrity of its "China Gold Supplier" program to at least 2,000 dealers that had subsequently defrauded buyers; the firm's share price dropped "abruptly" after the announcement.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] A statement from the firm reported that Yan Limin, the general manager of Alibaba.com at the time, had been dismissed in March for "misconduct"; Phil Muncaster of UK's *The Register* additionally reported that "a further 28 employees had been involved in dodgy dealings".
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The scandal was said to have placed the head of Alibaba Group, Jack Ma—who was described as having been furious over the scandal—in a position to personally fight to win back trust.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2013, Alibaba and six large Chinese logistics companies (including SF Express) established a company called Cainiao for delivery of packages in China.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] This network gradually grew to 14 local logistics companies in 2014.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2016, Alibaba's Taobao and Tmall, two of the world's largest and most popular online retail marketplaces, achieved a total transaction volume of 3 trillion yuan (US$478.6 billion).
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The company aims to double the transaction volume to 6 trillion yuan by 2020.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] As of February 2018, Taobao reached 580 million monthly active users, while Tmall achieved 500 million monthly active users.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It is also rapidly expanding its e-commerce network abroad.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba has also announced that it will invest 100 billion yuan over five years to build a global logistics network, underpinning an aggressive overseas expansion, and demonstrating Alibaba's commitment to building the most efficient logistics network in China and around the world.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It is investing a further 5.3 billion yuan in Cainiao Logistics to boost its stake to 51 percent from 47 percent.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The investment would value Cainiao, a joint venture of top Chinese logistics firms, at around US$20 billion.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba uses Cainiao software at its Belgian-European sales hub.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The software is able to access data about retailers, products, transport details and flows, a person familiar with the company's IT systems told the British newspaper *Financial Times*.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Chinese companies are legally obliged to pass on their data to China's authorities and security services.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The Belgium State Security Service is monitoring the hub in Lütich because of this fact and possible espionage.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] According to the *Financial Times*, Cainiao denied suggestions of wrongdoing, noting that the firm operates in compliance with relevant laws and regulations.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] According to the *Reuters*, Alibaba Group Holding Ltd has divested its logistics arm for $8.5 billion to a consortium led by investment firms Boyu Capital and Primavera Capital Group.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In conjunction with the company's 10th anniversary, Alibaba launched Alibaba Cloud in September 2009, aiming to build a cloud computing service platform, including e-commerce data mining, e-commerce data processing, and data customization.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It has R&D centres and operators in Hangzhou, Beijing, Hong Kong, Singapore, Silicon Valley and Dubai.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In July 2014, Alibaba Cloud entered into a partnership deal with Inspur.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba Cloud is the largest high-end cloud computing company in China.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2009, Alibaba acquired HiChina, the largest domain registration service and web hosting service company in China, and built it into Alibaba Cloud.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] On 28 July 2011, Alibaba Cloud released AliOS (formerly *Yun OS* and *Aliyun OS*), a Linux distribution designed for mobile devices.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In the 2017 Computing Conference in Hangzhou, Alibaba launched AliGenie, a China-based open-platform intelligent personal assistant.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It is currently used in the Tmall Genie smart speaker.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2018, Alibaba's Wanli Min presented City Brain, a technology geared towards urban solutions such as streamlining traffic, detecting accidents and improving transport efficiency.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] China's government designated Alibaba as one of its "AI champions" in 2018.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] On 27 July 2019, Alibaba unveiled a 64-bit RISC-V processor called the XuanTie-910 (Black Iron 910).
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It is a 12 nm 16-core with a clockrate of 2.5 GHz, and was designed by Alibaba's subsidiary T-Head (also known as Pingtouge).
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba claim the Xuantie-910 is faster than the ARM Cortex-A73 and is capable of 7.1 Coremark/MHz.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] On 25 September 2019, Alibaba announced an AI accelerator called the Hanguang 800.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The Hanguang 800 contains 17 billion transistors built with a 12 nm process and was designed by T-Head and DAMO Academy (Alibaba's research team).
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba claim it is capable of 78,563 images per second (IPS) inference and 500 IPS/W in ResNet-50.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba plans to lease Hanguang 800 cloud usage.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In April 2023, Alibaba revealed its plans to release Tongyi Qianwen, a ChatGPT-like chatbot.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Its name means "seeking an answer by asking a thousand questions".
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The company plans use Qwen in various business operations through existing services like DingTalk and Tmall Genie.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The company received at least 200,000 requests from various businesses to join its beta testing program.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba is also integrating Tongyi Qianwen into a digital assistant called Tingwu.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Tongyi Tingwu, the AI-powered assistant, can analyze multimedia content and generate a text summary from video and audio files.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In November 2024, QwQ-32B-Preview, a model focusing on reasoning similar to OpenAI's o1, was released under the Apache 2.0 License, although only the weights were released, not the dataset or training method.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] This model, developed by Alibaba's Qwen team, can process prompts up to 32,000 words long and features a unique self-fact-checking mechanism that allows it to solve complex logic puzzles and mathematical problems.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The model is not without limitations, as it may unexpectedly switch languages, get stuck in reasoning loops, and struggle with common sense reasoning.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Notably, the model is available under an Apache 2.0 license on Hugging Face, making it commercially accessible, though only certain components have been released.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Its development comes amid growing skepticism about traditional AI scaling laws and represents a new approach to AI reasoning that involves giving models more processing time to complete tasks.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In April 2025, Alibaba Cloud release Wan 2.1-FLF2V-14B Artificial Intelligence Video Generation Model under Apache license.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In December 2020, *The New York Times* reported that Alibaba had developed and marketed facial recognition and surveillance software configured to detect Uyghur faces and those of other ethnic minorities in China.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It aims to provide a platform for live events (e.g. concerts, plays, esports and sports events), as well as supporting content partners and leveraging Alibaba's data capability for offline shows.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It also provides the online digital distribution service 9Apps, which hosts downloadable content and applications.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In March 2014, Alibaba agreed to acquire a controlling stake in ChinaVision Media Group for $804 million.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The two firms announced they would establish a strategic committee for potential future opportunities in online entertainment and other media areas.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The company was renamed Alibaba Pictures Group (SEHK: 1060).
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In March 2015, Alibaba Group launched AliMusic as its music division.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Xiami Music and Tiantian Music are two of music streaming APP owned by AliMusic.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] AliMusic named Gao Xiaosong as the chairman and Song Ke as chief executive officer in July 2015.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2017, Tencent Music has expected $10bn IPO by signing a rights deal with Alibaba, strengthening its position within the important Chinese market.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In April 2014, Alibaba and Yunfeng Capital, a private equity company controlled by Alibaba's founder, Jack Ma, agreed to acquire a combined 18.5 percent stake in Youku Tudou, which broadcasts a series of popular television programs and other videos over the Internet.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba acquired a stake in Youku Tudou for $1.22 billion in 2014.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In its 2023 financial report, Alibaba disclosed a $1.2 billion impairment charge related to losses incurred by Youku.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Since restructuring in March 2023, the Digital Media and Entertainment Group has been led by Fan Luyuan as CEO.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In June 2025, Alibaba Pictures Group officially changed its name to Damai Entertainment Holdings Limited.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Its business has expanded from film to a diversified ecosystem including performances, IP commercial derivatives, TV series, artist management, and ticketing platforms.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In April 2026, Alibaba launched an artificial intelligence model for game development and video generation, part of its broader efforts to expand its AI offerings and compete with rivals such as Tencent.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2004, the Alibaba Group released Aliwangwang, an instant messaging software service for interactions between customer and online sellers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] By 2014, there are 50 million Aliwangwang users, making it the second-largest instant messaging tool in China.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In October 2013, the Alibaba's chairman Jack Ma announced that the Alibaba Group would no longer use Tencent's messaging application WeChat, and would henceforth promote its own messaging application and service, Laiwang.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In April 2014, Alibaba Group and UCWeb, a Chinese provider of mobile internet software technology and services, launched Shenma (神马), a mobile-only search engine, as part of a joint venture.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba's Y Projects Business Unit developed the *Xuexi Qiangguo* app, which is used to teach Xi Jinping Thought and other aspects of the history and ideology of the Chinese Communist Party.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2014, Alibaba Group founded DingTalk, an enterprise communication and collaboration platform.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Also known as Ding Ding, the app was developed as part of efforts to compete with rival Tencent's WeChat.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] DingTalk is managed by Alibaba's cloud computing division.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In October 2005, Alibaba Group formed a strategic partnership with Yahoo! and acquired Yahoo!
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] China, a Chinese portal previously launched on 24 September 1999 that focuses on Internet services like news, email, and search.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2005, Yahoo Inc. entered into a contract with Alibaba.com for $1 billion cash and gained 35% voting rights as the largest strategic investor.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba also got rights to Yahoo's brand in China and together the entity was managed by Alibaba's chairman at the time Jack Ma.In April 2013, Alibaba Group announced that, as part of the agreement to buy back the Yahoo!
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Mail stake, that it would suspend technological support for China Yahoo!
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Mail service and begin migration of Yahoo!
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Several options were offered to users to make the transition as smooth as possible, and Yahoo!
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] China users had four months to migrate their accounts to the Aliyun mail service, the Yahoo!
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Mail service in the United States, or to another third-party e-mail provider of the user's choice.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In August 2013 when users were asked to transfer accounts to Alilbaba's Alimail through a note on their login page.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In April it was clear that the closure was part of Yahoo's gradual exit from China since its 2005 stake acquisition in Alibaba.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Users with @yahoo.com.cn or @yahoo.cn could migrate all of their data to Alimail and continue receiving emails forwarded to their Yahoo addresses until December 31, 2014.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The music service that Yahoo China was offering had already shut down in January 2013.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] China closed its mail service on 19 August 2013.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] China accounts could be forwarded to an Alimail box until 31 December 2014.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Users were also allowed to transfer e-mail accounts to yahoo.com or any other e-mail service.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It is estimated there are no more than a million users with Yahoo!
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Mail for China and chances are they also own other e-mail accounts.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2004, the Alibaba Group launched Alipay, a third-party online payment platform.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It also provides an escrow service, in which buyers can verify whether they are happy with goods they have bought before releasing money to the seller.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Prior to Alipay, third-party payment was a legal grey area in China.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] As Alipay's popularity increased, it became accepted by Chinese regulators.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2010, the People's Bank of China issued administrative measures regarding non-financial payment services.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] These measures retroactively recognized the legal status of online third-party payment platforms like Alipay.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba Group spun off Alipay in 2010 in a controversial move.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2011, Alipay obtained a license to become one of the first licensed non-financial institutions to conduct payment operations.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] According to analyst research report, Alipay has the biggest market share in China with 300 million users and control of just under half of China's online payment market in February 2014.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2013, Alipay launched a financial product platform called Yu'ebao (余额宝).
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alipay partnered with the Tianhong Asset Management to launch it to the general public.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Yu'ebao offers an online money market account in which Alipay customers can deposit money and receive a higher interest rate than that available from banks.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It soon became China's largest online money market fund and prompted competitors like Baidu and Tencent to introduce alternatives.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The People's Bank of China supported the growth of such funds with a permissive regulatory environment initially but began increasing regulation of such funds in 2017.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] On 16 October 2014, the Alipay company was re-branded as Ant Financial Services (now Ant Group).
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] One of the factors for Alibaba's success in this platform is the company's payment system, which can handle simultaneous transactions with credit card, debit card, Alipay, Quick-pay, and online banking.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Ant Financial was ranked sixth in Fortune's *Change the World* list, recognized for the environmental impact of its *Ant Forest*, the world's largest platform for tracking individuals' carbon footprints.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2018, Ant Financial was the highest valued fintech company in the world, and the world's most valuable unicorn (start-up) company, with a valuation of US$150 billion.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In August 2020, Ant Financial, a subsidiary of Alibaba, launched the IPO program, valued at US$200 billion.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2014, Alibaba and Yunfeng Capital, a private equity firm, launched Alibaba Health when the two companies bought a 54% stake in CITIC 21CN for HK$1.33 billion (US$171 million).
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It is listed on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange as SEHK: 241.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It positions itself as a pharmaceutical e-commerce business and medical services.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In the same year, Alibaba acquired Chinese map supplier AutoNavi.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In April 2015, the group also reached an agreement to transfer its online B2C pharmacy, Tmall Medical (yao.Tmall.com), to AliHealth.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The integration provides consumers a wide range of pharmaceutical and health products available in China.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2015, Alibaba later launched its Shanghai-based sports division, AliSports, after a consolidation of some of the parent company's existing business units.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The new company's operations encompass television and digital sports rights, event operation, venue commercialization, copyright, media, business development, gaming, and ticketing.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] AliSports secured exclusive title sponsorship of the FIFA Club World Cup from 2015 to 2022.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The company announced a Champion of Champions rugby sevens tournament in 2017, to be played in Shanghai for the highest prize money ever offered in the sport.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In December 2015, Alibaba agreed to acquire the *South China Morning Post* and other media assets belonging to the group for a consideration of $266 million.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Although Alibaba promised editorial independence, vice-chairman Joseph Tsai said that Alibaba believes that "the world needs a plurality of views when it comes to China coverage.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] China's rise as an economic power and its importance to world stability is too important for there to be a singular thesis." The acquisition attracted media concerns over what this would mean for the newspaper's coverage.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Other subsidiaries of Alibaba include Hangzhou Ali Venture Capital and Alibaba Entrepreneurs Fund.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Hangzhou Ali Venture Capital (杭州阿里创业投资) is a company 80% owned by Jack Ma and another manager of Alibaba.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] For regulatory purpose, Alibaba Group did not own the company directly, but by pleading.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] It was considered as a subsidiary and/or consolidated entity of Alibaba Group.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Ali Venture Capital is a shareholder of Beijing Enlight Media and a domestic shareholder of China Unicom.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The Alibaba Entrepreneurs Fund is a non-profit making initiative launched by Alibaba Group in 2015.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba also has invested in more than ten startups in Hong Kong including DayDayCook, GoGoVan, WeLend and Qupital.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2019, Alibaba launched China-Russia flights in collaboration with Russian Post to assure fast shipping of products.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba owns the app Feizhu, which is a platform on which companies can sell tourism services such as day trips or cultural activities to Chinese consumers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] When Alibaba acquires shares in other businesses, it generally seeks to acquire a controlling stake and maintain control over the business operations.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba's main co-founder Jack Ma served as the executive chairman of the Alibaba Group from its founding until 10 September 2019.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Daniel Zhang succeeded Ma and has also served as Alibaba's CEO since 2015.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Michael Evans has served as Alibaba's president since 2015.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Jack Ma had stepped down as CEO in 2013 and chose Jonathan Lu as his successor.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The Alibaba Group under Lu was performing well, though there were rumors that Ma was growing distrustful in Lu's ability to lead the company.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Daniel Zhang, who served as COO of Alibaba under Lu, succeeded Lu as CEO in 2015.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] On 10 September 2018, Ma chose Zhang to succeed him as executive chairman of the Alibaba Group after his stepping down announcement, and this would go into effect in 1 year on 10 September 2019.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Since 2012, when Xi Jinping succeeded the CCP general secretary, the Chinese Communist Party (CCP) has had a CCP Committee secretary in place in the company and has over 2,000 party members as Alibaba employees.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In September 2019, the municipal government of Hangzhou announced that it was assigning government officials to work with tech companies and manufacturers in Zhejiang province, including Alibaba, in what city officials stated was an effort "to facilitate communication and expedite projects".
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] After the Russian invasion of Ukraine, Alibaba faced criticism for continuing to do business in Russia.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In August 2023, Ukraine's National Agency on Corruption Prevention designated the company an 'international sponsor of war' owing to it providing a platform for the sale of copper goods sourced from the occupied territories of Ukraine.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2023, Alibaba Group Holding Ltd has announced Joseph Tsai as the new chairman and Eddie Wu as the CEO.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] This move comes as the company seeks to revive growth in the post-crackdown era, with Tsai providing strategic direction and Wu driving operational excellence.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Around 44% of Alibaba shares are held by the general public and around 40% are held by institutions.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] In 2014, the Chinese government and Alibaba partnered to create the rural e-commerce expansion program Rural Taobao, which aimed to provide rural households with the same level of access to consumer goods that urban residents have and to facilitate the sale of agricultural goods through e-commerce.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] As of 2017, the program covered 16,500 villages.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Beginning in March 2016, Alibaba and the Communist Youth League began a collaboration to promote online entrepreneurship among rural Chinese youth.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Later that year, Alibaba signed other rural development agreements with the National Development and Reform Commission and Ministry of Agriculture.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] On 7 August 2021, Alibaba fired a manager who admitted to "indecent acts" with an inebriated employee.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The case highlighted issues of sexual harassment in the workplace.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba actively promotes female employment, collaborating with the All-China Women's Federation for community e-commerce events.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] The company also donates to UN Women to support female employment initiatives.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Half of Alibaba's employees are women, with one-third of leadership roles, especially in departments like human resources, held by women.
[src:alibaba-cloud/alibaba-group] Alibaba collaborates with Hangzhou's smart city initiative and efforts to digitize the economy and build a cashless city.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:alibaba-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] A **content delivery network** (**CDN**) or **content distribution network** is a geographically distributed network of proxy servers and corresponding data centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] CDNs provide high availability and performance ("speed") through geographical distribution relative to end users, and arose in the late 1990s to alleviate the performance bottlenecks of the Internet as it was becoming a critical medium.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Since then, CDNs have grown to serve a large portion of Internet content, including text, graphics and scripts, downloadable objects (media files, software, and documents), applications (e-commerce, portals), live streaming media, on-demand streaming media, and social media services.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] CDNs are a layer in the internet ecosystem.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Content owners such as media companies and e-commerce vendors pay CDN operators to deliver their content to their end users.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] In turn, a CDN pays Internet service providers (ISPs), carriers, and network operators for hosting its servers in their data centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] CDN vendors may cross over into other industries like security, DDoS protection and web application firewalls (WAF), and WAN optimization.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Content delivery service providers include Akamai Technologies, Cloudflare, Amazon CloudFront, Qwilt (Cisco), Fastly, CDN77, BunnyCDN, EdgeNext, and Google Cloud CDN.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] CDN nodes are usually deployed in multiple locations, often over multiple Internet backbones.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Benefits include reducing bandwidth costs, improving page load times, and increasing the global availability of content.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] The number of nodes and servers making up a CDN varies, depending on the architecture, some reaching thousands of nodes with tens of thousands of servers on many remote points of presence (PoPs).
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Others build a global network and have a small number of geographical PoPs.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Requests for content are typically algorithmically directed to nodes that are optimal in some way.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for performance, locations that are best for serving content to the user may be chosen.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] This may be measured by choosing locations that are the fewest hops or the shortest time to the requesting client, or the highest server performance, to optimize delivery across local networks.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for cost, locations that are the least expensive may be chosen instead.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] In an optimal scenario, these two goals tend to align, as **edge servers** that are close to the end user at the edge of the network may have an advantage in performance and cost.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Most CDN providers will provide their services over a varying, defined, set of PoPs, depending on the coverage desired, such as United States, Asia-Pacific, International or Global, etc.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] These sets of PoPs can be called "edges", "edge nodes", "edge servers", or "edge networks" as they would be the closest edge of CDN assets to the end user.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] CDN providers profit either from direct fees paid by content providers using their network, or profit from the user analytics and tracking data collected as their scripts are being loaded onto customers' websites inside their browser origin.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] As such these services are being pointed out as potential privacy intrusions for the purpose of behavioral targeting and solutions are being created to restore single-origin serving and caching of resources.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] In particular, a website using a CDN may violate the EU's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] For example, in 2021 a German court forbade the use of a CDN on a university website, because this caused the transmission of the user's IP address to the CDN, which violated the GDPR.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] CDNs serving JavaScript have also been targeted as a way to inject malicious content into pages using them.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Subresource Integrity mechanism was created in response to ensure that the page loads a script whose content is known and constrained to a hash referenced by the website author.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] The Internet was designed according to the end-to-end principle.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] This principle keeps the core network relatively simple and moves the intelligence as much as possible to the network end-points: the hosts and clients.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] As a result, the core network is specialized, optimized, and simplified to only forward data packets.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Content Delivery Networks extend the transport network by distributing on it a variety of intelligent applications employing techniques designed to optimize content delivery.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] The resulting tightly integrated overlay uses web caching, server-load balancing, request routing, and content services.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Web caches store popular content on servers that have the greatest demand for the content requested.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] These shared network appliances reduce bandwidth requirements, reduce server load, and improve the client response times for content stored in the cache.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Web caches are populated based on requests from users (pull caching) or based on preloaded content disseminated from content servers (push caching).
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Server-load balancing uses one or more techniques including service-based (global load balancing) or hardware-based (i.e. layer 4–7 switches, also known as a web switch, content switch, or multilayer switch) to share traffic among a number of servers or web caches.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Here the switch is assigned a single virtual IP address.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Traffic arriving at the switch is then directed to one of the real web servers attached to the switch.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] This has the advantage of balancing load, increasing total capacity, improving scalability, and providing increased reliability by redistributing the load of a failed web server and providing server health checks.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] A content cluster or service node can be formed using a layer 4–7 switch to balance load across a number of servers or a number of web caches within the network.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Request routing directs client requests to the content source best able to serve the request.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] This may involve directing a client request to the service node that is closest to the client, or to the one with the most capacity.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] A variety of algorithms are used to route the request.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] These include Global Server Load Balancing, DNS-based request routing, Dynamic metafile generation, HTML rewriting, and anycasting.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Proximity—choosing the closest service node—is estimated using a variety of techniques including reactive probing, proactive probing, and connection monitoring.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] CDNs use a variety of methods of content delivery including, but not limited to, manual asset copying, active web caches, and global hardware load balancers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Several protocol suites are designed to provide access to a wide variety of content services distributed throughout a content network.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] The Internet Content Adaptation Protocol (ICAP) was developed in the late 1990s to provide an open standard for connecting application servers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] A more recently defined and robust solution is provided by the Open Pluggable Edge Services (OPES) protocol.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] This architecture defines OPES service applications that can reside on the OPES processor itself or be executed remotely on a Callout Server.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Edge Side Includes or ESI is a small markup language for edge-level dynamic web content assembly.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] It is fairly common for websites to have generated content.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] It could be because of changing content like catalogs or forums, or because of the personalization.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] This creates a problem for caching systems.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] To overcome this problem, a group of companies created ESI.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] In *peer-to-peer (P2P)* content-delivery networks, clients provide resources as well as use them.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] This means that, unlike client–server systems, the content-centric networks can actually perform better as more users begin to access the content (especially with protocols such as Bittorrent that require users to share).
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] This property is one of the major advantages of using P2P networks because it makes the setup and running costs very small for the original content distributor.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] To incentive peers to participate in the P2P network, web3 and blockchain technologies can be used: participating nodes receive crypto tokens in exchange of their involvement.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] If content owners are not satisfied with the options or costs of a commercial CDN service, they can create their own CDN.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] A private CDN consists of PoPs (points of presence) that are only serving content for their owner.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] These PoPs can be caching servers, reverse proxies or application delivery controllers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] It can be as simple as two caching servers, or large enough to serve petabytes of content.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] When a private CDN is deployed within a company network, it is also referred as Entreprise CDN or **eCDN**.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Large content distribution networks may even build and set up their own private network to distribute copies of content across cache locations.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Such private networks are usually used in conjunction with public networks as a backup option in case the capacity of the private network is not enough or there is a failure which leads to capacity reduction.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Since the same content has to be distributed across many locations, a variety of multicasting techniques may be used to reduce bandwidth consumption.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Over private networks, it has also been proposed to select multicast trees according to network load conditions to more efficiently utilize available network capacity.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] The rapid growth of streaming video traffic required large capital expenditures by broadband providers in order to meet this demand and retain subscribers by delivering a sufficiently good quality of experience.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] To address this, telecommunications service providers have begun to launch their own content delivery networks as a means to lessen the demands on the network backbone and reduce infrastructure investments.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Because they own the networks over which video content is transmitted, telco CDNs have advantages over traditional CDNs.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] They own the last mile and can deliver content closer to the end-user because it can be cached deep in their networks.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] This deep caching minimizes the distance that video data travels over the general Internet and delivers it more quickly and reliably.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Telco CDNs also have a built-in cost advantage since traditional CDNs must lease bandwidth from them and build the operator's margin into their own cost model.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] In addition, by operating their own content delivery infrastructure, telco operators have better control over the utilization of their resources.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Content management operations performed by CDNs are usually applied without (or with very limited) information about the network (e.g., topology, utilization etc.) of the telco-operators with which they interact or have business relationships.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] These pose a number of challenges for the telco-operators who have a limited sphere of action in face of the impact of these operations on the utilization of their resources.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] In contrast, the deployment of telco-CDNs allows operators to implement their own content management operations, which enables them to have a better control over the utilization of their resources and, as such, provide better quality of service and experience to their end users.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] In June 2011, StreamingMedia.com reported that a group of TSPs had founded an Operator Carrier Exchange (OCX) to interconnect their networks and compete more directly against large traditional CDNs like Akamai and Limelight Networks, which have extensive PoPs worldwide.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] This way, telcos are building a Federated CDN offering, which is more interesting for a content provider willing to deliver its content to the aggregated audience of this federation.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] It is likely that in a near future, other telco CDN federations will be created.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] They will grow by enrollment of new telcos joining the federation and bringing network presence and their Internet subscriber bases to the existing ones.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] The Open Caching specification by Streaming Video Technology Alliance defines a set of APIs that allows a Content Provider to deliver its content using several CDNs in a consistent way, seeing each CDN provider the same way through these APIs.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Combining several CDN services allow Content Providers to not rely on a single CDN service, especially concerned to deal with high peak audience during live events.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] There are several ways to allocate traffic to a particular CDN among the list, either client-side CDN selection, or server-side (at the Content Provider's origin) or cloud-side (in the middle, between the content origin and the audience).
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] CDN selection criteria can be performance, availability and cost.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Traditionally, CDNs have used the IP of the client's recursive DNS resolver to geo-locate the client.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] While this is a sound approach in many situations, this leads to poor client performance if the client uses a non-local recursive DNS resolver that is far away.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] For instance, a CDN may route requests from a client in India to its edge server in Singapore, if that client uses a public DNS resolver in Singapore, causing poor performance for that client.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Indeed, a recent study showed that in many countries where public DNS resolvers are in popular use, the median distance between the clients and their recursive DNS resolvers can be as high as a thousand miles.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] In August 2011, a global consortium of leading Internet service providers led by Google announced their official implementation of the edns-client-subnet IETF Internet Draft, which is intended to accurately localize DNS resolution responses.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] The initiative involves a limited number of leading DNS service providers, such as Google Public DNS, and CDN service providers as well.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] With the edns-client-subnet EDNS0 option, CDNs can now utilize the IP address of the requesting client's subnet when resolving DNS requests.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] This approach, called end-user mapping, has been adopted by CDNs and it has been shown to drastically reduce the round-trip latencies and improve performance for clients who use public DNS or other non-local resolvers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] However, the use of EDNS0 also has drawbacks as it decreases the effectiveness of caching resolutions at the recursive resolvers, increases the total DNS resolution traffic, and raises a privacy concern of exposing the client's subnet.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Virtualization technologies are being used to deploy virtual CDNs (vCDNs) (also known as a software-defined CDN or sd-CDN) with the goal to reduce content provider costs, and at the same time, increase elasticity and decrease service delay.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] With vCDNs, it is possible to avoid traditional CDN limitations, such as performance, reliability and availability since virtual caches are deployed dynamically (as virtual machines or containers) in physical servers distributed across the provider's geographical coverage.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] As the virtual cache placement is based on both the content type and server or end-user geographic location, the vCDNs have a significant impact on service delivery and network congestion.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] To boost performance, delivery to clients from servers can use alternate non-HTTP protocols such as WebRTC and WebSockets.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] In 2017, Addy Osmani of Google started referring to software solutions that could integrate naturally with the Responsive Web Design paradigm (with particular reference to the <picture> element) as **Image CDN**s.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] The expression referred to the ability of a web architecture to serve multiple versions of the same image through HTTP, depending on the properties of the browser requesting it, as determined by either the browser or the server-side logic.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] The purpose of Image CDNs was, in Google's vision, to serve high-quality images (or, better, images perceived as high-quality by the human eye) while preserving download speed, thus contributing to a great User experience (UX).
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Arguably, the *Image CDN* term was originally a misnomer, as neither Cloudinary nor Imgix (the examples quoted by Google in the 2017 guide by Addy Osmani) were, at the time, a CDN in the classical sense of the term.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Shortly afterwards, though, several companies offered solutions that allowed developers to serve different versions of their graphical assets according to several strategies.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] Many of these solutions were built on top of traditional CDNs, such as Akamai, CloudFront, Fastly, Edgecast and Cloudflare.
[src:alibaba-cloud/content-delivery-network] At the same time, other solutions that already provided an image multi-serving service joined the Image CDN definition by either offering CDN functionality natively (ImageEngine) or integrating with one of the existing CDNs (Cloudinary/Akamai, Imgix/Fastly).
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] A **data center** is a facility used to house computer systems and associated components, such as telecommunications and storage systems.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Data centers are critical infrastructure for the storage and processing of information, and they support the global financial system, cloud services, machine learning, and artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Data centers vary widely in terms of size, power and water requirements, and overall structure.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Hyperscale and colocation facilities collectively account for approximately 74% of U.S. server energy consumption as of 2023, a share that has grown significantly over the past decade as workloads have migrated away from enterprise on-premises infrastructure.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Since IT operations are crucial for business continuity, a data center generally includes redundant or backup components.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Other important design considerations are power supply, network infrastructure, environmental controls (e.g., cooling, fire suppression), and various measures for physical and data security.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Large data centers operate at an industrial scale, requiring significant energy.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Estimated global data center electricity consumption in 2024 was around 415 terawatt hours (TWh), or about 1.5% of global electricity demand.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The International Energy Agency (IEA) projects that data center electricity consumption could double by 2030.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The rapid growth of data center infrastructure has prompted regulatory debates in multiple jurisdictions regarding tax incentives, electricity grid impacts, water consumption, and compatibility with state and national climate commitments.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Rapid growth of the AI industry is leading to strain on electric grids and increased electricity costs for consumers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] This in turn has drawn growing opposition to new data centers from local people who would bear the burdens of social and environmental impacts, such as energy and water use, while faraway actors and institutions would receive the projects' benefits.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] These opposition movements have materialized especially in parts of Europe, the U.S., and South America.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Billions of dollars in projects were halted or delayed by data center resistances in the U.S. between May 2024 and June 2025.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Data centers are usually classified according to their ownership model, scale, and intended use.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] However, these classifications are not mutually exclusive from each other, and they may overlap depending on the operational structure and service model of the particular data center.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Enterprise data centers are owned and operated by a single organization for their own internal information technology (IT) needs, rather than for commercial hosting of other companies' data.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] They used to be essential infrastructures; as in 2014, enterprise data centers accounted for over 60% of the U.S. server energy consumption, but this share fell sharply to about 10% by 2023 as workloads migrated to hyperscale and colocation facilities.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Energy efficiency at an enterprise data center tends to be significantly lower than at hyperscale facilities due to its cooling, which can account for over 30% of electricity consumption at enterprise sites, compared to roughly 7% at efficient hyperscale data centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The shift away from enterprise facilities toward cloud and colocation infrastructure is one of the defining structural trends of the previous decade.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Colocation centers provide shared physical infrastructure, such as power, cooling, space, etc., to multiple tenants who lease space rather than building their own facilities.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Colocation data centers reduce expenditure for organizations while enabling operators to achieve economies of scale in power procurement and cooling efficiency.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Some of the largest data centers in the world are colocation centers, and this category accounted for about 22% of worldwide data center capacity as of 2024, making them the second-largest category by capacity after hyperscale facilities.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Major colocation providers include Equinix, Switch, COPT, and Digital Realty, which operate facilities across multiple continents.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Hyperscale data centers are large-scale facilities, typically exceeding 100 megawatts of power capacity, designed to support massive, scalable computing workloads for cloud services, AI training, and large-scale data processing.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] By the end of 2024, there were 1,136 operational hyperscale data centers globally, a figure that doubled over the previous five years, with the U.S. accounting for approximately 54% of total hyperscale capacity.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In particular, the three largest operators, Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud, collectively account for approximately 59% of all hyperscale data center capacity globally.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] As a growing trend, hyperscale data centers represented about 41% of worldwide data center capacity in 2024 and are projected to exceed 60% by 2029 as enterprise on-premises infrastructure continues to decline.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Moreover, as artificial intelligence (AI) is becoming widely used, AI data centers are being built more rapidly, and they can consume as much electricity as 100,000 households, more than conventional data centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Since 2024, there has been widespread grassroots Opposition to AI Data Centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Edge data centers are smaller facilities, typically ranging from 1 to 10 megawatts.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] They are positioned closer to end users or data sources to reduce network latency and support real-time applications, such as autonomous vehicles, industrial automation, and content delivery.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Unlike hyperscale data centers, edge data centers are intentionally distributed across many locations rather than consolidated, with deployments occurring in urban areas, cell tower sites, as well as industrial locations.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The growth of edge computing infrastructure has been tied to the expansion of 5G wireless networks and the increasing use of Internet of Things (IoT) devices, which generate data that is more efficiently processed near its source than transmitted to a centralized data center.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Micro data centers (MDCs) are access-level data centers that are smaller in size than traditional data centers but provide the same features.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] They are typically located near the data source to reduce communication delays, as their small size allows several MDCs to be spread out over a wide area.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] MDCs are suited to user-facing, front end applications.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] They are commonly used in edge computing and other areas where low latency data processing is needed.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Modularity and flexibility are key elements in allowing a data center to grow and change over time.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Data center modules are pre-engineered, standardized building blocks that can be configured and moved as needed.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] A modular data center may consist of data center equipment contained within shipping containers or similar portable containers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Components of the data center can be prefabricated and standardized, which facilitates moving if needed.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] These modular data centers are useful for IT disaster recovery.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Mobile data centers are also used to move large quantities of data, by physically transporting the hardware that contains it, and in cryptocurrency mining, where fleets of mobile data centers are transported to take advantage of cheaper sources of energy.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Data centers have their roots in the huge computer rooms of the 1940s, typified by the Electronic Numerical Integrator and Computer (ENIAC), one of the earliest examples of a data center.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Early computer systems were complex to operate and maintain, and required a special environment in which to operate.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Many cables were necessary to connect all of the components, and methods to accommodate and organize these were devised such as standard racks to mount equipment, raised floors, and cable trays (installed overhead or under the elevated floor).
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] A single mainframe required a great deal of power and had to be cooled to avoid overheating.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Security became important – computers were expensive, and were often used for government and military purposes.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] As such, basic design guidelines for controlling access to the computer room were devised.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] During the microcomputer industry boom of the 1980s, computers started to be deployed everywhere, in many cases with little or no care about operating requirements.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] However, as information technology (IT) operations started to grow in complexity, organizations grew aware of the need to control IT resources.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The availability of inexpensive networking equipment, coupled with new standards for the network structured cabling, made it possible to use a hierarchical design that put servers in a specific room inside the company.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The use of the term *data center*, as applied to specially designed computer rooms, started to gain popular recognition about this time.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] During the dot-com bubble (1997–2000), there was a boom in data center construction because companies needed fast Internet connectivity and non-stop operation to establish their Internet presence.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The global data center market saw steady growth in the 2010s, with a notable acceleration in the latter half of the decade.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] According to Gartner, worldwide data center infrastructure spending reached $200 billion in 2021, representing a 6% increase from 2020 despite economic challenges posed by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In 2024, global energy consumption from data centers was 620 TWh, with 80% of that consumption concentrated in the U.S., China, and the United Kingdom.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Colocation centers were the most common category worldwide, with 4,799 colocation centers in 127 countries.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In that year, the largest data center in the world was Citadel, owned by Switch, at the Tahoe Reno Industrial Center in Reno, Nevada, occupying 7.2 million square feet.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Growth of the data center industry has prompted local resistance.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] A 2023 survey found social mobilizations against the industry in Europe, the U.S., and South America.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] These movements expressed concern about the centers' energy and water use, pollution, and impact on agriculture or the landscape.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] A 2026 poll by *Politico* suggested that resistance to growth of the industry would make candidates' stance on data centers a significant issue for voters in the U.S.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The U.S. hosted 5,381 data centers in March 2024, the highest number of any country worldwide, accounting for 40% of the global market in 2023.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] As of 2023, about 80% of U.S. data center load was concentrated in 15 states, led by Virginia and Texas.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] As of 2025, roughly one third of America's data centers were in three states: Virginia (643), Texas (395), and California (319).
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The largest concentration of data centers in the world is in Northern Virginia, with over 250 facilities in the region.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In 2025, Georgia was the fastest growing data center hub in the U.S., having enacted several state tax exemptions for the industry and hosting between 100 and 150 centers in the state.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Local governments have responded to the growing industry in Georgia with a variety of local ordinances to guide permitting of these facilities.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The consultancy firm McKinsey & Co., projected U.S. demand to double to 35 gigawatts (GW) by 2030, up from 17 GW in 2022.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] A study published by the Electric Power Research Institute (EPRI) in May 2024 estimated that data centers could consume between 4.6% and 9.1% of the country's electricity generation by 2030.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] GDP growth was only 0.1% without the investments in data centers for artificial intelligence.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Data centers house critical computing resources in a controlled environment and must generally operate with very high availability.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Key design elements include providing power for the equipment, temperature and humidity control, cabling, fire safety, and security.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] For this reason, a data center has to offer a secure environment that minimizes the chances of a security breach.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Industry research company International Data Corporation (IDC) puts the average age of a data center at nine years old.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Gartner, another research company, says data centers older than seven years are obsolete.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The growth in data (163 zettabytes by 2025) is one factor driving the need for data centers to modernize.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Rapid obsolescence of data center equipment was a concern by at least 2007, and in 2011, Uptime Institute was concerned about aging equipment.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The topology proposed in this document is intended to be applicable to any size data center.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Telcordia GR-3160, *NEBS Requirements for Telecommunications Data Center Equipment and Spaces*, provides guidelines for data center spaces within telecommunications networks, and environmental requirements for the equipment intended for installation in those spaces.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] These criteria were developed jointly by Telcordia and industry representatives.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] They may be applied to data center spaces housing data processing or IT equipment.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Power supplies, either back up or continuous onsite power, consist of one or more uninterruptible power supplies, battery banks, diesel, gas turbine, and/or gas engine generating sets.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Greater primary fuel energy efficiency can be achieved with the use of cogeneration technology, generating electricity, heating, and cooling onsite.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] To prevent single points of failure, all elements of the electrical systems, including backup systems, are typically given redundant copies, and critical servers are connected to both the *A-side* and *B-side* power feeds.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] This arrangement is often made to achieve N+1 redundancy in the systems.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Static transfer switches are sometimes used to ensure instantaneous switchover from one supply to the other in the event of a power failure.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Options for low-voltage cable routing might include data cabling that is routed through overhead cable trays; raised floor cabling, both for security reasons and to avoid the extra cost of cooling systems over the racks; and anti-static tiles for flooring, especially in low-cost data centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Maintaining suitable temperature and humidity levels is critical to preventing equipment damage caused by overheating.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Overheating can cause components (usually the silicon or copper of the wires or circuits) to melt, causing loose connections and fire hazards.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Typical temperature control methods include air conditioning and indirect cooling, such as the use of outside air, indirect evaporative cooling units, and seawater cooling.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Airflow management is the practice of achieving data center cooling efficiency by preventing the recirculation of hot exhaust air and by reducing bypass airflow.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Common approaches include hot-aisle/cold-aisle containment and the deployment of in-row cooling units, which position cooling directly between server racks to intercept exhaust heat before it mixes with room air.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Humidity control prevents moisture and related issues.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] For example, excess humidity can cause dust to adhere more readily to fan blades and heat sinks, impeding air cooling and leading to higher temperatures.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Cold aisle containment is done by exposing the rear of equipment racks, while the fronts of the servers are enclosed with doors and covers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] This is similar to how large-scale food companies refrigerate and store products.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Computer cabinets/server farms are often organized for containment of hot/cold aisles.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Proper air duct placement prevents cold and hot air from mixing.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Rows of cabinets are paired to face each other so the cool and hot air intakes and exhausts do not mix air, which would severely reduce cooling efficiency.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Alternatively, a range of underfloor panels can create efficient cold air pathways directed to the raised-floor vented tiles.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Either the cold aisle or the hot aisle can be contained.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Another option is fitting cabinets with vertical exhaust duct chimneys.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Hot exhaust pipes/vents/ducts can direct the air into a plenum space above a dropped ceiling and back to the cooling units or to outside vents.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] With this configuration, traditional hot/cold aisle configuration is not required.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Data centers feature fire protection systems, including passive and active design elements, as well as implementation of fire prevention programs in operations.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Smoke detectors are usually installed to provide early warning of a fire.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Although the main room usually does not allow wet pipe-based systems due to the fragile nature of circuit boards, there are systems that can be used in the rest of the facility or in cold/hot aisle air circulation systems that are closed systems.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] These include sprinkler systems and misting, the latter of which uses high pressure to create extremely small water droplets and can be used in sensitive rooms due to the nature of the droplets.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] However, there are other means to put out fires, especially in Sensitive areas, usually using gaseous fire suppression, of which Halon gas was the most popular, until the negative effects of producing and using it were discovered.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Physical access to data centers is usually restricted.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Layered security often starts with fencing, bollards, and mantraps.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Video camera surveillance and permanent security guards are almost always present if the data center is large or contains sensitive information.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Fingerprint recognition is starting to become commonplace.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Logging access is required by some data protection regulations; some organizations tightly link this to access control systems.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Multiple log entries can occur at the main entrance, entrances to internal rooms, and at equipment cabinets.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Access control at cabinets can be integrated with intelligent power distribution units, so locks are networked through the same appliance.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Data center transformation takes a step-by-step approach through integrated projects carried out over time.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] This differs from a traditional method of data center upgrades, which takes a serial and siloed approach.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Typical projects within a data center transformation initiative include standardization/consolidation, virtualization, automation, and security.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Data center consolidation consists of reducing the number of data centers and avoiding *server sprawl* (both physical and virtual), which often includes replacing aging data center equipment.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] This process is aided by standardization, which makes these systems follow a uniform set of configurations to simplify and improve efficiency.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Automating tasks such as provisioning, configuration, patching, release management, and compliance are other ways in which data centers can be upgraded.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] These changes are needed not just when facing fewer skilled IT workers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Lastly, security initiatives integrate the protection of virtual systems with existing security for physical infrastructures.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The first raised floor computer room was made by IBM in 1956 to allow access for wiring.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] During the 1970s, raised floors became more common because they allow cool air to circulate more efficiently.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] A raised floor standards guide (GR-2930) was developed by Telcordia Technologies, a subsidiary of Ericsson.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The "lights-out" data center, also known as a darkened or dark data center, is a data center that has largely eliminated the need for direct access by personnel, except under extraordinary circumstances.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Due to the lack of need for staff to enter the data center, it can be operated without lighting.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] All of the devices are accessed and managed by remote systems, with automation programs used to perform unattended operations.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In addition to the energy savings, reduction in staffing costs, and the ability to locate the site further from population centers, implementing a lights-out data center also reduces the threat of malicious attacks upon the infrastructure.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) regulations require monitoring of noise levels inside data centers if noise exceeds 85 decibels.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The average noise level in server areas of a data center may reach as high as 92–96 dB(A).
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Residents living near data centers have described the sound as "a high-pitched whirring noise 24/7", saying "It's like being on a tarmac with an airplane engine running constantly ...
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] External sources of noise include HVAC (heating, ventilation, and air conditioning) equipment and energy generators.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Location factors include proximity to power grids, telecommunications infrastructure, networking services, transportation lines, and emergency services.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Other considerations should include flight paths, neighboring power drains, geological risks, and climate (associated with cooling costs).
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Local political considerations, such as availability of subsidies and lack of opposition, are also important factors in locating data centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Various metrics exist to measure the data-availability that results from data-center availability beyond 95% uptime, with the top of the scale counting how many *nines* can be placed after *99%*.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The costs of avoiding downtime should not exceed the cost of the downtime itself.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Dynamic infrastructure provides the ability to intelligently, automatically, and securely move workloads within a data center anytime, anywhere, for migrations, provisioning, to enhance performance, or build co-location facilities.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] It also facilitates performing routine maintenance on either physical or virtual systems, all while minimizing interruption.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] A related concept is Composable Infrastructure, which allows for the dynamic reconfiguration of the available resources to suit needs, only when needed.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Communications in modern data centers are most often based on networks running the Internet protocol suite.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Data centers contain a set of routers and switches that transport traffic between the servers and to the outside world, which are connected according to the data center network architecture.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Redundancy of the internet connection is often provided by using two or more upstream service providers (see Multihoming).
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Some of the servers at a data center are used for running the basic internet and intranet services needed by internal users in the organization, e.g., e-mail servers, proxy servers, and DNS servers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Network security elements are also usually deployed: firewalls, VPN gateways, intrusion detection systems, and so on.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Also common are monitoring systems for the network and some of the applications.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Additional off-site monitoring systems are also typical, in case of a failure of communications inside the data center.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Energy consumption and the environmental impacts it creates are a central issue for data centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Power draw ranges from a few kilowatts (kW) for small server racks to several tens of megawatts (MW) for large facilities.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Modern hyperscale data centers can exhibit power densities exceeding 100 times those of conventional office buildings, primarily due to the high concentration of servers and cooling systems required to manage continuous digital workloads.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] For higher power density facilities, electricity costs are a dominant operating expense and account for over 10% of the total cost of ownership (TCO) of a data center.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] As of 2024, data centers in the U.S. are primarily powered by natural gas, which supplies 40% of their electricity (with renewable energy at 24%, nuclear at about 20%, and coal at about 15%).
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The *Associated Press* reported that electricity for AI data centers in the U.S. would likely come from natural gas or oil, as companies prefer using currently available power plants, which primarily use fossil fuels.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Fossil energy is also often cheaper in locations where data centers are developed, and experts believe that energy demands from generative AI and data centers would be difficult to fulfill with renewable energy alone.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Some companies such as Google, Amazon, and Meta have expressed interest in nuclear power for their data centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] As of 2020, according to the IEA, solar photovoltaic-generated electricity is at its lowest cost in history.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Other data centers, including xAI's Colossus, OpenAI's Stargate, and Meta's Prometheus use their own off-grid natural gas plants.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Electric vehicle and lithium-ion batteries have also been used for powering data centers, including for Colossus.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Power utility companies make upgrades to their infrastructure to handle demands of new data centers, and the price for these changes typically falls on residential or smaller commercial consumers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In 2025, the Mountain Valley Pipeline announced plans to expand its capacity by 25% to meet energy needs for data centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In December 2025, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) published a unanimous order allowing data centers in the U.S. to have a direct connection with power plants.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] United States Secretary of Energy Chris Wright expressed support for un-retiring coal plants to power AI data centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Electricity demands from AI data centers have slowed or reversed the retirement of peaking power plants in the U.S.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] For example, in 2025, Southern Company announced that energy use from data centers would prevent the company from retiring coal-fired power plants as it had earlier promised.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In Nevada, the Desert Research Institute (DRI) calculated that 35% of the state's energy production could go to data centers by the year 2030 if all projects planned in the state as of 2026 are completed.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] DRI also stated, in areas where there are clusters of data centers, local consumers may end up paying the extra cost of expanding infrastructure.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In 2024, data centers were estimated to account for about 1.5% of global electricity consumption (approximately 415 TWh) and around 1% of greenhouse gas emissions according to U.S.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] However, the rapid expansion is causing projections to rise sharply.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Due to accelerated demand from AI, data center's global electricity consumption is projected to more than double to around 945 TWh by 2030 in the IEA's base-case scenario, which represents just under 3% of 2030 total global electricity consumption.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] This growing electricity demand, much of which is still generated by fossil fuels, increases the potential environmental impacts.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In addition to operational energy demand, embodied life cycle emissions should be considered, which include the extraction, manufacturing, transportation, and recycling or disposal of materials used in the construction of facilities and hardware.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Global data center carbon dioxide emissions are projected to rise from an estimated 220 million tonnes in 2024 to 300–320 million tonnes by 2035.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In 2024, Google and Microsoft each consumed more power than over 100 countries.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] As a result, there is increasing industry pressure for decarbonization.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Companies are pursuing direct clean energy agreements, such as Tencent who has pledged to be carbon neutral by 2030, and Microsoft's 2024 agreement to re-open the Three Mile Island nuclear power plant to provide 100% of the electric power for its AI data centers for 20 years.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The most commonly used energy efficiency metric for data centers is power usage effectiveness (PUE), calculated as the ratio of total power entering the data center divided by the power used by IT equipment.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] PUE measures the percentage of power used by overhead devices (cooling, lighting, etc.).
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The average U.S. data center has a PUE of 2.0, meaning two watts of total power (overhead + IT equipment) for every watt delivered to IT equipment.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] State-of-the-art data centers are estimated to have a PUE of roughly 1.2.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Google publishes quarterly efficiency metrics from its data centers in operation.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] PUEs of as low as 1.01 have been achieved with two-phase immersion cooling.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The EPA has an Energy Star rating for standalone or large data centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] To qualify for the ecolabel, a data center must be within the top quartile in energy efficiency of all reported facilities.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The Energy Efficiency Improvement Act of 2015 (U.S.) requires federal facilities—including data centers—to operate more efficiently.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] California's Title 24 (2014) of the California Code of Regulations mandates that every newly constructed data center must have some form of airflow containment in place to optimize energy efficiency.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The European Union (EU) also has a similar initiative: EU Code of Conduct for Data Centres.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Efficiency improvements and renewable energy integration are helping offset some emissions, but fossil fuels remain a major electricity source for data center operations worldwide.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In 2011, server racks in data centers were designed for more than 25 kW, and the typical server was estimated to waste about 30% of the electricity it consumed.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The energy demand for information storage systems is also rising.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] A high-availability data center is estimated to have a 1 MW demand and consume $20 million in electricity over its lifetime, with cooling representing 35% to 45% of the data center's total cost of ownership.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Calculations show that in two years, the cost of powering and cooling a server could be equal to the cost of purchasing the server hardware.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Research in 2018 showed that a substantial amount of energy could still be conserved by optimizing IT refresh rates and increasing server use.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Research for optimizing task scheduling is also underway, with researchers looking to implement energy-efficient scheduling algorithms that could reduce energy consumption by anywhere between 6% and 44%.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In 2011, Facebook, Rackspace, and others founded the Open Compute Project (OCP) to develop and publish open standards for greener data center computing technologies.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] As part of the project, Facebook published the designs of its server, which it had built for its first dedicated data center in Prineville.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Making servers taller left space for more effective heat sinks and enabled the use of fans that moved more air with less energy.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] By not buying commercial off-the-shelf servers, energy consumption due to unnecessary expansion slots on the motherboard and unneeded components, such as a graphics card, was also saved.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In 2016, Google joined the project and published the designs of its 48V DC shallow data center rack.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] This design had long been part of Google data centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] By eliminating the multiple transformers usually deployed in data centers, Google had achieved a 30% increase in energy efficiency.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In 2017, sales for data center hardware built to OCP designs topped $1.2 billion and are expected to reach $6 billion by 2021.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Power is the largest recurring cost to the user of a data center.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In 2008, the ASHRAE recommended a temperature range of 64.4 °F (18.0 °C) to 80.6 °F (27.0 °C), though some data centers could operate at higher temperatures.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] However, cooling at or below 70 °F (21 °C) wastes money and energy.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Furthermore, overcooling equipment in environments with a high relative humidity can expose equipment to a high amount of moisture that facilitates the growth of salt deposits on conductive filaments in the circuitry.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] A **power and cooling analysis**, also referred to as a thermal assessment, measures the relative temperatures in specific areas as well as the capacity of the cooling systems to handle specific ambient temperatures.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Power cooling density is a measure of how much square footage the center can cool at maximum capacity.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The cooling of data centers is the second largest power consumer after servers, with cooling taking about 7% to 30% of energy usage (depending on efficiency), compared to an average of 60% of energy used by servers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] An energy efficiency analysis measures the energy use of data center IT and facilities equipment.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] A typical energy efficiency analysis measures factors such as a data center's Power Use Effectiveness (PUE) against industry standards, identifies mechanical and electrical sources of inefficiency, and identifies air-management metrics.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] However, the limitation of most current metrics and approaches is they do not include IT in the analysis.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Case studies have shown that by addressing energy efficiency holistically in a data center, major efficiencies can be achieved that are not possible otherwise.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Thermal zone mapping uses sensors and computer modeling to create a three-dimensional image of the hot and cool zones in a data center.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] This information can help identify optimal positioning of data center equipment.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] For example, critical servers might be placed in a cool zone that is serviced by redundant AC units.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Data centers use a lot of power, consumed via two main usages: the power required to run the equipment and the power required to cool the equipment.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Power efficiency reduces the first category.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Cooling cost reduction through natural means includes location decisions.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] When the focus is avoiding good fiber connectivity, power grid connections, and people concentrations to manage the equipment, a data center can be miles away from users.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Mass data centers like Google or Facebook do not need to be near population centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Arctic locations that can use outside air, which provides cooling, are becoming more popular.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Countries with favorable conditions, such as Canada, Finland, Sweden, Norway, and Switzerland are trying to attract cloud computing data centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Singapore lifted a three-year ban on new data centers in April 2022.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] A major data center hub for the Asia-Pacific region, Singapore lifted its moratorium on new data center projects in 2022, granting four new projects, but rejecting more than 16 data center applications from over 20 received.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] It is very difficult to reuse the heat that comes from air-cooled data centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] For this reason, data center infrastructures are more often equipped with heat pumps.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The rapid growth of artificial intelligence (AI) and high-performance computing workloads has increased attention on data center power infrastructure, particularly the relationship between electrical reliability, deployment timelines, energy costs, and decarbonization objectives.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Industry publications have described phased approaches to infrastructure development that enable operators to deploy power capacity rapidly while maintaining pathways toward lower-carbon energy systems as technologies, fuel availability, grid capacity, and economics evolve.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Recent industry discussion has also emphasized "speed-to-power" as a significant consideration in data center development, reflecting the growing importance of securing electrical capacity and resilient power systems within increasingly compressed project timelines.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In the 2020s, the rapid growth of data center construction gave rise to policy debates over tax incentives, electricity grid, water resources, and climate commitments.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] By 2024, at least 36 U.S. states had introduced specific tax incentives aimed at attracting data center investment, most often in the form of sales tax exemptions on servers, networking equipment, and electricity.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Virginia hosts the largest concentration of data centers in the U.S., and a December 2024 audit by its Joint Legislative Audit and Review Commission (JLARC) put the industry's annual contribution at roughly 74,000 jobs and $9.1 billion in gross state product.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The audit reported that the state's sales and use tax exemption was claimed by about 90% of operators and that reduced state revenue by an estimated $928 million in fiscal year 2023.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Thus, JLARC concluded that ending the exemption would likely shrink Virginia's share of new data center investment.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Economists have debated the effectiveness of such incentives more broadly.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Further, research by Timothy Bartik of the Upjohn Institute estimated that economic development incentives change firm location decisions in only 2% to 25% of cases.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In response to tax exemption policies, several jurisdictions have started to reevaluate incentives for data centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In 2024, the Georgia General Assembly passed legislation to terminate the state's data center sales tax exemption.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] However, the bill was ultimately vetoed by Governor Brian Kemp.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In another case in 2026, the Virginia Senate voted 28 to 12 to phase out the state's data center sales tax exemption as part of broader budget negotiations.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Most large data centers use water for evaporative cooling of their servers, and the volumes involved have drawn growing scrutiny.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] A 2021 study in *npj Clean Water* estimated that U.S. data centers directly consume about 1.7 billion liters of water per day, with up to 57% of that drawn from potable supplies, and noted that fewer than one-third of operators measured their water use at the time.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] A separate study published in *Environmental Research Letters* found that about one-fifth of direct water use by U.S. data centers came from moderately or highly water-stressed watersheds, and that nearly half of the country's servers ran on electricity drawn from water-stressed regions.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] According to a 2024 Berkeley Lab report, data centers in the U.S. had used approximately 17 billion gallons of water.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The same report expected hyperscale data centers specifically to use 16 to 33 billion gallons of water per year by 2028.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In Virginia, the December 2024 JLARC audit reported that data centers in the state consumed about 2.1 billion gallons of water in 2023, an 86% increase since 2019, and that roughly one-third of that came from reclaimed water rather than potable supplies.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The audit recommended that local governments be authorized to require water-use estimates as part of the data center permitting process.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] There is no federal U.S. standard requiring data center operators to disclose water consumption, and access to facility-level data has often been limited by non-disclosure agreements (NDAs) with host municipalities.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In 2022, the city of The Dalles, Oregon, settled a public records lawsuit brought by *The Oregonian*, after which Google ended its nationwide practice of treating site-level water use as a trade secret.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In 2025, several states considered legislation to require data centers to disclose water use, including bills in Virginia, California, and New Jersey, although each was vetoed by the state's governor that year.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The growth of data center electricity demand in the 2020s has prompted regulatory debates over grid capacity, transmission planning, and how the costs of new infrastructure should be allocated among customers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The 2024 Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory (LBNL) report on U.S. data center energy use, prepared at the request of the U.S.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Congress, estimated that data centers accounted for about 4.4% of national electricity consumption in 2023 and projected a rise to between 6.7% and 12% by 2028, depending on growth scenarios.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In 2025, the IEA projected that data centers would account for nearly half of new U.S. electricity demand growth through 2030.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC), the federally designated electric reliability organization for the U.S., identified data centers as the single largest driver of projected demand growth in its 2024 long-term reliability assessment.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Additionally, NERC documented a voltage event in the PJM Interconnection region in July 2024, in which roughly 1,500 megawatts of data center load disconnected simultaneously across about 60 facilities.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] How the costs of meeting this demand are shared has also become a central policy question.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The JLARC audit in 2024 estimated that, without any changes to how rates are designed, typical residential customers of Dominion Energy Virginia could see their bills rise by $14 to $37 per month by 2040 because of data center-driven grid investment.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] As such, the report recommended creating a separate customer rate class for large data centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Some researchers have urged caution in interpreting demand projections.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Furthermore, a 2024 commentary in the journal *Joule* argued that public estimates of future data center electricity use vary widely and that utilities have historically over-forecasted load growth, and called for more transparent data on actual facility-level consumption.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The growth of data centers has raised questions about whether the renewable energy commitments made by their operators are consistent with broader climate goals.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Many large operators report meeting electricity-related emissions targets through annual purchases of renewable energy certificates (RECs) or matching their total annual consumption with renewable generation.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In 2022, a study by *Nature Climate Change* analyzed 115 companies with Science Based Targets.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] It found that about 42% of their reported Scope 2 emissions reductions disappeared once REC-based claims were excluded.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] This directly suggests that some corporate climate progress reflected accounting choices rather than actual reductions in grid emissions.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In response, some operators and researchers have proposed 24/7 carbon-free energy matching.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Under this approach, every hour of a facility's electricity use must be matched with carbon-free generation on the same regional grid.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The authors found that annual or volumetric matching did little to cut grid emissions under current U.S. policy.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Hourly 24/7 matching cut more, but it cost about $13 to $30 more per megawatt-hour.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] The tension between data center expansion and corporate climate goals has also become apparent in the operators' own disclosures of information.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] In 2024, Google reported its greenhouse gas emissions had risen by about 48% since 2019, attributing the increase in large part to data center electricity use associated with AI workloads.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Similarly, Microsoft reported in 2024 that its emissions had risen by about 29% since 2020, citing the construction and operation of new data centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p01] Moreover, the IEA projected in 2025 that global data center carbon dioxide emissions could peak at around 320 million tonnes by 2030 before declining slightly through 2035, with the trajectory depending heavily on the carbon intensity of the electricity supplied to new facilities.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Data centers have significant impacts on local ecologies, politics, and utility infrastructure.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Political and economic incentives such as tax breaks, land deals, or government subsidies drive data center growth in areas where these incentives are available.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Data centers are frequently located in rural areas, where they may displace agriculture.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Growth in the data center industry has prompted several debates about environmental impacts, especially the massive energy and water demands.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] The supply chains, emissions, and e-waste also impose significant planetary impacts, raising questions of environmental injustice toward marginalized communities that frequently bear these burdens.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Multiple studies and experts have found that data centers do not bring high-paying jobs to local communities in proportion to the tax subsidies they receive.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] The rapid expansion of AI data centers has raised significant concerns over their water consumption, particularly in drought-prone regions.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] According to the IEA, a single 100-megawatt data center, using 2400 MWh of electricity per day, can use up to 2,000,000 litres (530,000 US gal) of water per day.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] The electricity use is equivalent to that of 60,000–120,000 households in the U.S., while water use is equivalent about 6,500 households.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Water usage can be divided into three categories: on-site (direct usage from data centers), off-site (indirect usage from electricity), and supply-chain (water usage from manufacturing processes).
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] On-site water use refers to the direct water consumed by the data center for the cooling of its equipment.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Water is used specifically for space humidification (adding moisture to the air), evaporative cooling systems (cooling air before entering server rooms), and cooling towers (removing heat from the facility).
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Off-site water use is the indirect water usage from the electricity generated in data centers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] It is estimated that 56% of U.S. data centers' electricity comes from fossil fuels in thermal power stations, which use water to generate power via steam.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Lastly, data centers consume water through the process of AI chip and server manufacturing.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] These chips, specifically, consume a vast amount of ultrapure water for fabrication and cooling of semiconductor plants.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] While this scope of water usage is not as significant as on-site and off-site water usage, it is still a contributing factor.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Globally, since 2022, more than two-thirds of new data centers have been built in water-stressed areas, including Texas, Arizona, Saudi Arabia, and India, where freshwater scarcity is already a critical issue.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] The global water footprint of data centers is estimated at 560 billion litres (150×10^9 US gal) annually, a figure projected to double by 2030 due to increasing AI demand.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] In regions like Aragon, Spain, Amazon's planned data centers are licensed to withdraw 755,720 cubic metres (612.67 acre⋅ft) of water per year, sparking conflicts with farmers who rely on the same dwindling supplies.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Similar tensions have arisen in Chile, the Netherlands, and Uruguay, where communities protest the diversion of water for tech infrastructure.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Tech companies, including Microsoft, Google, and Amazon, have pledged to become "water positive" by 2030, aiming to replenish more water than they consume.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] However, critics argue that such commitments often rely on water offsetting, which does not address acute local shortages.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] At least 59 additional data centers are planned for water-stressed U.S. regions by 2028, and AI's global water demand is projected to reach 6.6 billion cubic metres (1,700×10^9 US gal) by 2027.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Data centers generate significant electronic waste (e-waste) due to the frequent replacement of hardware such as servers, GPUs, CPUs, memory, and storage devices, often every 2–5 years to meet demands for digital transformation and AI.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Globally, e-waste totaled 62 million metric tons in 2022, with generative AI projected to contribute 1.2 to 5 million metric tons annually by 2030, including valuable metals like copper and gold, and hazardous substances such as lead and mercury.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] In the U.S., data centers contribute to an annual loss of $10 billion in discarded e-waste value, including $4 billion in precious metals.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Only 22% of global e-waste is formally collected and recycled, exacerbating environmental pollution and health risks in informal processing sites, often in developing countries where exported waste is handled.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] From a political ecology perspective, data center e-waste highlights power imbalances in resource management and environmental justice, as tech corporations benefit from tax incentives while externalizing costs to marginalized communities through toxic exports and landfill burdens.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] This ties into debates on the commons, where shared resources like metals are depleted without equitable governance.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Mitigation strategies include modular hardware designs, secure data erasure for reuse, and extended producer responsibility policies to reduce waste by up to 86% in optimized scenarios.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] According to one 2025 energy model, the U.S. could see energy prices increase 8% nationally by 2030.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Higher electricity prices are already occurring in some regions, particularly those with lots of data centers like Santa Clara, California, and parts of upstate New York.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Data centers have also generated concerns in Northern Virginia about whether residents will have to foot the bill for future power lines.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] It has also made it harder to develop housing in London.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] A Bank of America Institute report in July 2024 found that increased demand for electricity due in part to AI has been pushing electricity prices higher and is a significant contributor to electricity inflation.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] A Harvard Law School report in March 2025 found that because utilities are increasingly in competition to attract data center contracts from big tech companies, they are likely hiding subsidies to those trillion-dollar companies in power prices by raising costs for American consumers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Data centers have increasingly been analyzed through the lens of political ecology, which explores the intersections of power, politics, and environmental change in technological infrastructure.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Scholars argue that these facilities reshape urban and rural landscapes by existing in marginalized or post-industrial areas, often repurposing abandoned sites while promising economic revitalization through job creation and tax revenues.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] For instance, hyperscale data centers in rural towns like Prineville, Oregon, or Luleå, Sweden, challenge traditional core-periphery dynamics but can exacerbate global inequalities in digital access and resource distribution.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] In the context of digital transformation, data centers enable the expansion of cloud computing, AI, and machine learning, but at significant ecological and social costs.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Critics from science and technology studies (STS) highlight how corporate sustainability pledges, such as carbon neutrality targets by companies like Microsoft and Google, often rely on offsets and renewable subsidies that privatize benefits while causing social and environmental harms.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] This ties into debates on the commons, where data centers' intensive use of public resources (like electricity grids and water supplies) represents an enclosure, with tech firms receiving tax breaks and priority access at the expense of local communities.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Jobs created by data centers tend to be temporary or few in number.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] A study found the productivity increases enabled by data centers are multiple times larger than gross external damages.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Social mobilizations against data centers help shape the discourse around growth of the industry, raise public awareness of issues data centers present, and may impact public policy.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Groups opposed to new data center projects have expressed concern that digital infrastructure exploits local resources 'to the benefit of actors and institutions residing elsewhere'.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] This may occur when data being processed in a facility belongs to actors in other countries, but local people bear the burdens of water and energy use.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] In the U.S., bipartisan community resistance to data center development has grown, with residents voicing concerns about water scarcity, rising utility bills, noise pollution, and urban sprawl.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Facilities in rural areas of the U.S. have been focal points for local resistance.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Data Center Watch reported that multiple projects collectively worth $64 billion had been stopped or delayed between May 2024 and March 2025.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] An additional $98 billion worth of projects were blocked or delayed between March and June 2025.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] A Gallup poll taken in March 2026 reported seven out of ten Americans oppose data center projects in their area.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Outside of the U.S., protests in the Netherlands led to a temporary national ban on new mega-centers in 2022.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] In Chile, protests by activists to protect water reserves led to Google withdrawing plans to build a data center.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] In the United Kingdom, "March Against the Machines" protests were held.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Residents have been concerned about air, water, and noise pollution, as well as property devaluation, traffic, and the risk of fires.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Other environmental concerns involving AI data centers include e-waste and the embodied energy of construction materials, such as concrete and cement.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] data center, they would orbit above the dawn / dusk transition of the planet.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Housing data centers in space has been proposed for low Earth orbit (LEO).
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] The theoretical advantages are that of space-based solar power, in addition to aiding in weather forecasting and weather prediction computation from weather satellites, and the ability to freely scale up.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] However, it is difficult to design cooling systems in space, as convection is not available and sunlight causes large temperature fluctuations.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] Other challenges include damage from cosmic rays and micrometeorites.
[src:alibaba-cloud/data-center-p02] The design and shape of data centers could change rapidly in the not-too-distant future with the advent of new technologies, such as quantum computing, biocomputation, and synthetic DNA data storage, as examples.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] In computing, **elasticity** is defined as "the degree to which a system is able to adapt to workload changes by provisioning and de-provisioning resources in an autonomic manner, such that at each point in time the available resources match the current demand as closely as possible".
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] Elasticity is a defining characteristic that differentiates cloud computing from previously proposed distributed computing paradigms, such as grid computing.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] The dynamic adaptation of capacity, e.g., by altering the use of computing resources, to meet a varying workload is called "elastic computing".
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] In the world of distributed systems, there are several definitions according to the authors; some consider the concepts of scalability a sub-part of elasticity, others as being distinct.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] Elasticity aims to match the amount of resources allocated to a service with the amount of resources it actually requires, avoiding over- or under-provisioning.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] **Over-provisioning**, i.e., allocating more resources than required, should be avoided as it may incur extra costs (monetary, energy, operational, etc.) for unused or underutilized resources.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] For example, if a website is over-provisioned with two cloud computing resources to handle current demand that only requires one resource, the costs of maintaining the second resource would effectively be wasted.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] Elasticity can be illustrated through an example of a service provider who wants to run a website on the cloud.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] At moment $t_{0}$ , the website is unpopular and a single machine is sufficient to serve all users.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] At moment $t_{1}$ , the website suddenly becomes popular, and a single machine is no longer sufficient to serve all users.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] Based on the number of web users simultaneously accessing the website and the resource requirements of the web server, ten machines are needed.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] An elastic system should immediately detect this condition and provision nine additional machines from the cloud to serve all users responsively.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] At time $t_{2}$ , the website becomes unpopular again.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] The ten machines currently allocated to the website are mostly idle and a single machine would be sufficient to serve the few users who are accessing the website.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] An elastic system should immediately detect this condition and deprovision nine machines, releasing them to the cloud.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] A cloud virtual machine (VM) can be acquired at any time by the user; however, it may take up to several minutes for the acquired VM to be ready to use.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] The VM startup time is dependent on factors such as image size, VM type, data center location, number of VMs, etc.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] Cloud providers have different VM startup performance.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] This implies that any control mechanism designed for elastic applications must consider the time needed for the resource provisioning actions to take effect.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] Elastic applications can allocate and deallocate resources on demand for specific application components.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] This makes cloud resources volatile, and traditional monitoring tools which associate monitoring data with a particular resource, such as Ganglia or Nagios, are no longer suitable for monitoring the *behavior* of elastic applications.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] For example, during its lifetime, a data storage tier of an elastic application might add and remove data storage VMs due to cost and performance requirements, varying the number of used VMs.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] Thus, additional information is needed in monitoring elastic applications, such as associating the logical application structure over the underlying virtual infrastructure.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] When deploying applications in cloud infrastructures (IaaS/PaaS), stakeholder requirements need to be considered in order to ensure that elastic behavior meets stakeholder needs.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] Traditionally, the optimal trade-off between cost and quality or performance is considered; however, for real world cloud users, requirements regarding elastic behavior are more complex and target multiple dimensions of elasticity (e.g., SYBL).
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] Cloud applications vary in type and complexity, with multiple levels of artifacts deployed in layers.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] Controlling such structures must take into consideration a variety of issues.
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] Elastic strategies on in cloud computing can take advantage of control-theoretic methods (e.g., predictive control has been experimented in cloud computing scenarios by showing considerable advantages with respect to reactive methods).
[src:alibaba-cloud/elastic-computing] One approach to multi-level elastic clouc control is rSYBL.
